\series bold 
Using Mathematics to Derive How Centripetal Acceleration Depends on Radius
 and Speed 
\layout Standard

You haven't done any experiments yet to see how centripetal acceleration
 depends on the radius of the circle and the speed of the object.
 You can use the rules of mathematics and the definition of acceleration
 to derive the relationship between speed, radius, and magnitude of centripetal
 acceleration.
 
\layout Standard


\series bold 
Activity 4: How Does ac Depend on v and r?
\series default 
 
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom 20mm 
(a) Do you expect you would need more centripetal acceleration or less centripet
al acceleration to cause an object moving at a certain speed to rotate in
 a smaller circle? In other words, would the magnitude, a
\begin_inset Formula \( _{c} \)
\end_inset 

, have to increase or decrease as r decreases if circular motion is to be
 maintained? Explain.
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom 20mm 
(b) Do you expect you would need more centripetal acceleration or less centripet
al acceleration to cause an object to rotate at a given radius r if the
 speed v is increased? In other words, would the magnitude, a
\begin_inset Formula \( _{c} \)
\end_inset 

, have to increase or decrease as v increases if circular motion is to be
 maintained? Explain.
\layout Standard

You should have guessed that it requires more acceleration to move an object
 of a certain speed in a circle of smaller radius and that it also takes
 more acceleration to move an object that has a higher speed in a circle
 of a given radius.
 Lets use the definition of acceleration in two-dimensions and some accepted
 mathematical relationships to show that the magnitude of centripetal accelerati
on should actually be given by the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{c}=\frac{v^{2}}{r}\qquad [Eq.\: 1]\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

In order to do this derivation you will want to use the following definition
 for acceleration
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \overrightarrow{a}\right\rangle =\frac{\overrightarrow{v_{2}}-\overrightarrow{v_{1}}}{t_{2}-t_{1}}=\frac{\Delta \overrightarrow{v}}{\Delta t}\qquad [Eq.\: 2]\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


